Thanks for the suggestions — I’ve reviewed the points and here’s the plan from my side:

1. Photon acceleration
We can disable Photon by switching the cluster runtime to a standard (non-Photon) runtime. Given the current workload is primarily ETL and not heavily compute-intensive SQL, this should not impact performance significantly and will help reduce cost.

2. Autoscaling configuration
Agreed on enabling autoscaling. I will configure the cluster with a minimum of 1 worker and a maximum of 8 workers so that compute scales based on demand and avoids idle cost.

3. Dashboard refresh frequency (30 mins)
Currently, the refresh runs every 30 minutes. Since this uses the BICOE endpoint, I agree this may lead to unnecessary compute usage.
As a next step, I propose:

Moving to a controlled schedule (hourly during business hours and reduced frequency overnight), and
Implementing time-based logic within the job to avoid unnecessary runs, given the current scheduling limitation of a single cron per job.

This should help optimise cost while still maintaining sufficient visibility for monitoring.

Photon acceleration has been disabled, the cluster is configured with autoscaling (min 1, max 8) to optimise compute usage, and the dashboard refresh has been separated into a dedicated job running hourly between 4 AM and 8 PM with overnight refresh stopped to reduce cost.
